<h1><a class='u' href='#___top' title='click to go to top of document'
name="NAME"
>NAME <img alt='^' src='http://st.pimg.net/tucs/img/up.gif'></a></h1>

<p>feature - Perl pragma to enable new features</p>

<h1><a class='u' href='#___top' title='click to go to top of document'
name="SYNOPSIS"
>SYNOPSIS <img alt='^' src='http://st.pimg.net/tucs/img/up.gif'></a></h1>

<pre class="sh_perl">    use feature qw(switch say);
    given ($foo) {
        when (1)          { say &#34;\$foo == 1&#34; }
        when ([2,3])      { say &#34;\$foo == 2 || \$foo == 3&#34; }
        when (/^a[bc]d$/) { say &#34;\$foo eq &#39;abd&#39; || \$foo eq &#39;acd&#39;&#34; }
        when ($_ &#62; 100)   { say &#34;\$foo &#62; 100&#34; }
        default           { say &#34;None of the above&#34; }
    }

    use feature &#39;:5.10&#39;; # loads all features available in perl 5.10</pre>

<h1><a class='u' href='#___top' title='click to go to top of document'
name="DESCRIPTION"
>DESCRIPTION <img alt='^' src='http://st.pimg.net/tucs/img/up.gif'></a></h1>

<p>It is usually impossible to add new syntax to Perl without breaking some existing programs. This pragma provides a way to minimize that risk. New syntactic constructs, or new semantic meanings to older constructs, can be enabled by <code>use feature &#39;foo&#39;</code>, and will be parsed only when the appropriate feature pragma is in scope.</p>

<h2><a class='u' href='#___top' title='click to go to top of document'
name="Lexical_effect"
>Lexical effect</a></h2>

<p>Like other pragmas (<code>use strict</code>, for example), features have a lexical effect. <code>use feature qw(foo)</code> will only make the feature &#34;foo&#34; available from that point to the end of the enclosing block.</p>

<pre class="sh_perl">    {
        use feature &#39;say&#39;;
        say &#34;say is available here&#34;;
    }
    print &#34;But not here.\n&#34;;</pre>

<h2><a class='u' href='#___top' title='click to go to top of document'
name="no_feature"
><code>no feature</code></a></h2>

<p>Features can also be turned off by using <code>no feature &#34;foo&#34;</code>. This too has lexical effect.</p>

<pre class="sh_perl">    use feature &#39;say&#39;;
    say &#34;say is available here&#34;;
    {
        no feature &#39;say&#39;;
        print &#34;But not here.\n&#34;;
    }
    say &#34;Yet it is here.&#34;;</pre>

<p><code>no feature</code> with no features specified will turn off all features.</p>

<h2><a class='u' href='#___top' title='click to go to top of document'
name="The_&#39;switch&#39;_feature"
>The &#39;switch&#39; feature</a></h2>

<p><code>use feature &#39;switch&#39;</code> tells the compiler to enable the Perl 6 given/when construct.</p>

<p>See <a href="/~flora/perl-5.14.2/pod/perlsyn.pod#Switch_statements" class="podlinkpod"
>&#34;Switch statements&#34; in perlsyn</a> for details.</p>

<h2><a class='u' href='#___top' title='click to go to top of document'
name="The_&#39;say&#39;_feature"
>The &#39;say&#39; feature</a></h2>

<p><code>use feature &#39;say&#39;</code> tells the compiler to enable the Perl 6 <code>say</code> function.</p>

<p>See <a href="/~flora/perl-5.14.2/pod/perlfunc.pod#say" class="podlinkpod"
>&#34;say&#34; in perlfunc</a> for details.</p>

<h2><a class='u' href='#___top' title='click to go to top of document'
name="the_&#39;state&#39;_feature"
>the &#39;state&#39; feature</a></h2>

<p><code>use feature &#39;state&#39;</code> tells the compiler to enable <code>state</code> variables.</p>

<p>See <a href="/~flora/perl-5.14.2/pod/perlsub.pod#Persistent_Private_Variables" class="podlinkpod"
>&#34;Persistent Private Variables&#34; in perlsub</a> for details.</p>

<h2><a class='u' href='#___top' title='click to go to top of document'
name="the_&#39;unicode_strings&#39;_feature"
>the &#39;unicode_strings&#39; feature</a></h2>

<p><code>use feature &#39;unicode_strings&#39;</code> tells the compiler to use Unicode semantics in all string operations executed within its scope (unless they are also within the scope of either <code>use locale</code> or <code>use bytes</code>). The same applies to all regular expressions compiled within the scope, even if executed outside it.</p>

<p><code>no feature &#39;unicode_strings&#39;</code> tells the compiler to use the traditional Perl semantics wherein the native character set semantics is used unless it is clear to Perl that Unicode is desired. This can lead to some surprises when the behavior suddenly changes. (See <a href="/~flora/perl-5.14.2/pod/perlunicode.pod#The_&#34;Unicode_Bug&#34;" class="podlinkpod"
>&#34;The &#34;Unicode Bug&#34;&#34; in perlunicode</a> for details.) For this reason, if you are potentially using Unicode in your program, the <code>use feature &#39;unicode_strings&#39;</code> subpragma is <b>strongly</b> recommended.</p>

<p>This subpragma is available starting with Perl 5.11.3, but was not fully implemented until 5.13.8.</p>

<h1><a class='u' href='#___top' title='click to go to top of document'
name="FEATURE_BUNDLES"
>FEATURE BUNDLES <img alt='^' src='http://st.pimg.net/tucs/img/up.gif'></a></h1>

<p>It&#39;s possible to load a whole slew of features in one go, using a <i>feature bundle</i>. The name of a feature bundle is prefixed with a colon, to distinguish it from an actual feature. At present, the only feature bundle is <code>use feature &#34;:5.10&#34;</code> which is equivalent to <code>use feature qw(switch say state)</code>.</p>

<p>Specifying sub-versions such as the <code>0</code> in <code>5.10.0</code> in feature bundles has no effect: feature bundles are guaranteed to be the same for all sub-versions.</p>

<h1><a class='u' href='#___top' title='click to go to top of document'
name="IMPLICIT_LOADING"
>IMPLICIT LOADING <img alt='^' src='http://st.pimg.net/tucs/img/up.gif'></a></h1>

<p>There are two ways to load the <code>feature</code> pragma implicitly :</p>

<ul>
<li>By using the <code>-E</code> switch on the command-line instead of <code>-e</code>. It enables all available features in the main compilation unit (that is, the one-liner.)</li>

<li>By requiring explicitly a minimal Perl version number for your program, with the <code>use VERSION</code> construct, and when the version is higher than or equal to 5.10.0. That is,
<pre class="sh_perl">    use 5.10.0;</pre>

<p>will do an implicit</p>

<pre class="sh_perl">    use feature &#39;:5.10&#39;;</pre>

<p>and so on. Note how the trailing sub-version is automatically stripped from the version.</p>

<p>But to avoid portability warnings (see <a href="/~flora/perl-5.14.2/pod/perlfunc.pod#use" class="podlinkpod"
>&#34;use&#34; in perlfunc</a>), you may prefer:</p>

<pre class="sh_perl">    use 5.010;</pre>

<p>with the same effect.</p>
</li>
</ul>

